<DOC><DOCNO> AP891220-0113 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-89 1243EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Toyota     12-20 0203</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Toyota,0208</SECOND><HEAD>Toyota Reportedly Expects Record Domestic Sales in 1990</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Toyoda is correct for president's name.</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Toyota Motor Corp. expects its 1990 domestic salesto grow 8 percent from this year while exports remain stable,President Shoichiro Toyoda was quoted as saying Wednesday.   Surging domestic demand will boost domestic sales for a seventhconsecutive year, to a record 2.48 million vehicles next yearcompared with this year's estimated sales of 2.30 million, KyodoNews Service quoted Toyoda as saying.   The predictions of Japan's largest automaker come in the face ofrecent loss of market share due to the brisk performance of NissanMotor Co., Japan's No. 2 automaker, which has been cutting intoToyota's dominance in the domestic market, Kyodo noted.   While Toyota's 8 percent domestic sales growth outpaces Nissan'sestimate of 4 percent growth in domestic sales to 1.37 millionvehicles next year, Nissan officials announced Tuesday they expectoverseas production to grow a hefty 7 percent in 1990 to 683,000.   Toyota's exports are expected to remain flat at 1.68 millionunits next year, Toyoda said.   Toyota, which accounts for 41.8 percent of total domestic sales,plans to boost its share to around 42.8 percent, he said.</TEXT></DOC>